{
  "query": "What is the evidence for how different tillage practices affect weed populations in arable fields in Mediterranean agriculture?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across Mediterranean-relevant studies, reduced tillage was associated with more weeds in some or all comparisons in seven replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Italy, Lebanon, Spain, Turkey, and the USA; one of these also reported fewer weeds under reduced tillage in some comparisons, and one Italian replicated, randomized, controlled study found similar weed numbers between reduced and conventional tillage [1399]. For weed species responses under reduced tillage, two replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Spain and Turkey found similar numbers of weed species, while one replicated, randomized, controlled study from the USA found a different weed community composition compared to conventional tillage [1399]. For no tillage, three replicated, controlled studies (two randomized) from Italy and Spain found more weeds in some comparisons than under conventional tillage; four replicated, controlled studies (three randomized) from Italy, Spain, and the USA reported inconsistent differences (sometimes more, sometimes fewer), and one replicated, randomized, controlled study from Lebanon found similar weed numbers with or without tillage [1397]. For weed species under no tillage, one replicated, randomized, controlled study from Italy found more species than under conventional tillage, while three replicated, controlled studies (two randomized) from Italy and Spain found similar species numbers with or without tillage [1397]. Broader European evidence on reduced tillage also reports increased numbers of some weeds and/or weed species compared to conventional management, though effects can be negative, neutral, or inconsistent depending on taxa and context; two studies noted crop type affected weed numbers across tillage regimes [126].",
