{
  "query": "What are the benefits and drawbacks of using organic fertilizer instead of inorganic fertilizer for crop production and soil health in Mediterranean systems?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from Mediterranean contexts indicates mixed effects on crop production and multiple soil-related changes. For crop yields, replicated studies from Italy, Spain, and Greece found higher, lower, or similar yields with organic versus inorganic fertilizers depending on crop and comparison (11 studies total; food crops mostly in Italy and Spain; one forage crop study in Spain reported higher alfalfa yield in one of two comparisons) [1350]. For soil properties, studies from France, Italy, Spain, Turkey, Portugal, and Mediterranean countries reported: higher soil organic matter in some comparisons, though several studies found similar levels [1366]; nitrogen and ammonium sometimes higher and sometimes similar, nitrate sometimes lower or similar [1366]; phosphorus sometimes higher, sometimes lower, or similar; potassium sometimes higher or similar [1366]; soil pH often similar, but sometimes higher or lower with organic fertilizer depending on study [1366]. For soil biota and structure, microbial biomass was often higher in some comparisons, while other soil organisms (bacteria, nematodes, mites) were sometimes fewer or showed inconsistent differences; soil aggregation was sometimes greater, though some studies found no difference [1366]. For greenhouse gases, carbon dioxide emissions were sometimes higher or similar; soils sometimes absorbed more methane or showed similar methane absorption; nitrous oxide emissions were sometimes similar or lower with organic fertilizer, with lower emissions reported particularly with solid organic fertilizers compared to inorganic, while liquid organic fertilizers did not show this reduction; compost increased organic matter, nutrients, and microbial biomass compared to manure in one Italian study; slurry applications were associated with methane absorption while manure applications emitted methane in one Spanish study [1366].",
  "action_ids": [
